{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_lavender_ver01/data/sn88078775/00340580758/1920102901/0327.xml":{"full_text":"f.-.-lF as\nMI\n3\ni\n'A\nr\u201dT-\n-Si\nPAGE TWO\nHowe News\nAccepts Job in Mt. Vernon\nAlbert Reichert, the well known\nplumber, has accepted a position in\nMt. Vernon.\nVisiting in Barberton\nMr. and Mrs. J. M. Heft and son\nOtto, of 689 West Main street, are\nvisiting their daughter Mrs. Wilkie\nRaddiff, of Barberton, Ohio,\nmade the trip by automobile.\n\nThey\nElks\u2019 Glee Glub\nThe\nElks\u2019 Glee Club made its first\nappearance at the Auditorium\npublic\nMonday evening, in compliment to the\naccompanist of the club, George M.\nFenbcrg. The club made a decided\nhit and were enthusiastically received\nby a large audience.\nWedding Announcement\nAt a reception given by Mrs. Fred\nWright at her home on Eddy street\nlast Friday evening, the engagement\nof Miss Mary Carl, the accomplished\ndaughter of Mr. Louis F. Carl, and\nMr. Frederick F. Wright was an\nnounced. The date for the wedding\nwas not given.\nFine Musical Entertainment\nMusic lovers will be enabled to en\njoy a rare treat on Tuesday evening,\nNov. 2, when Harry Leiter, in light\nopera, will appear at the high school\nauditorium. This is the first number\nof the Lyceum entertainments given\nunder the auspices of Licking Aerie\nFraternal Order of Eagles, and those\nwho fail to attend will miss a most\nexcellent entertainment.\nNew Music Store in Thornville\nDowd Schopen, the Arcade music\ndealers, have opened a branch store in\nThornville, and will carry a complete\nstock of the celebrated Starr pianos,\nplayer pianos, phonographs and\nrecords. This will enable the resi\ndents of that portion of the county to\npurchase anything in the musical line,\nfrom a large and complete assortment\nwithout traveling many unnecessary\nmiles.\nTempest in a Teapot\nThe hulabaloo raised by some over\nzealous city officials who claimed that\nthe carnival company, which recently\nexhibited at Moundbuilders Park, had\noccupied territory w\u2019ithin the city\nlimits and had defrauded the city out\nof a small fortune by neglecting to\npay the $100 per day license fixed by\nour thrifty city dads, was proved to\nbe somewhat premature when the\ncity engineer, city solicitor and\nnumerous other municipal officers\nvisited the park last week with a load\nof transits, levels, tapelines and the\nLord knows what, and discovered that\nthe territory in question was not\nwithin the city limits.\nWe have a fine lot of Cigars that\nwe are selling for 5c, worth 7 and 8c.\ntf ERMAN\u2019S DRUG STORE\nAuto Phone 1028\nr\" ENGLANDER\nWIT-CDGE. iPRWG\nBuys Hospital Property\nWiliam Hamilton, of the1 Hamilton\nSons Car Co., has purchased the\nprivate hospital property on Gran\nville street. Consideration $16,000.\nBroken Arm Reset\nThe injury of Elmer Dover, the fif\nteen year old son of William Dover,\nwho sustained a broken arm a month\nago, is not improving as it should,\nand the boy was taken to the city\nhospital Wednesday where the' frac\nture was examined and the arm reset\nby a Columbus specialist.\nHallowe\u2019en Party\nThursday evening of last week\nMisses Jane Ratschen and Inez Rowe\nentertained a large number of friends\nat the home of the former with a hal\nJowe\u2019en party. The costumes and\ndecorations were appropriate to the\noccasion and a delightful evening,\nduring which elegant refreshments\nwere served, was enjoyed by all.\nA. E. Willert Leaves Newark\nMr. A. E. Willert, formerly man\nager of the Woolworth store, but for\nseveral years past acting as sales\nmanager for the Wehrle company,\nhas resigned to accept the position\nof general sales manager for the\nWhittaker-Glessner Co., a branch of\nthe Wheeling Steel Car Corporation,\none of the biggest industrial corpora\ntions in the United States. Mr. Wil\nlert will enter upon his duteis Nov.\n1st, and the best wishes of his host\nof friends in Newark will accompany\nhim to his new field of labor.\nThe union label stands for moral\nity, cleanliness, honesty, chivalry\ntward woman and protection of the\nyoung.\n360\n00\nTHE BEST\nCORSET\nFOR STOUT\nWOMEN.\nLIGHTBUT\nSTRONG\nIf\ndealer\nLADIES\u2019 ALL WOOL SWEATERS\nREDUCED FOR QUICK SELLING\nTHEY ARE BEAUTIES\u2014ALL NEW FALL STYLES.\nTuxedo and Slipovers\u2014in wanted colors. Black, White, Brown,\nTan, Purple, Peacock, Turquois, American Beauty.\nIf you need a sweater, and every woman needs several, come in\nsoon. They are real bargains. Priced $12.00, $10.98, $10.00, $8.75.\nBEAUTIFUL SILVERTONE YARNS\nAll Colors now in. 2 oz. balls\nFour Fold Germantown and Knitting Worsted\nBrush Wool, W hite, Black, Tan....\nPure Camels Hair, Natural Color\nShetland and Saxony\n4 oz. Hanks, Firm Texture, for Boys\u2019 and Men\u2019s Wear.\nYARNS MAY BE FASHIONED INTO MANY USEFUL GIFTS.\nHANDKERCHIEF LINENS, WHITE AND COLORS\nTo be had in 12-inch strips, thread drawn $1.00\nThis makes three \u201ckerchiefs\u201d D. M. C. boil-proof threads.\n17 WEST CHURCH STREET\nDENTIST\nON SALE FORA\nk. SHORT TIME\nit. send money\nand waist meu\n(over clothing) and w\u00ae will send you\none for trial. Po\u00bbtag\u00abs prepaid.\nMBJO IB Girsn aSTTION INSTITUTE\nD\u00bbpt M. 23 Ir'-ni* Pis-e Kr\u00bb fork\nCORSETTIERS\n24^ West Main Stree\nCapudine\nUTT ST\nDEPENDABLE ABJOLUTELY\nFOR HEADACHES\nSold\nor by u use\nlaw\nhero by fumifure dealers\nand department store*\nJtNLLAKW.'W SJIdNO UX CO.\n$(AvVork -Brooklyn, CJucn^o'\nTHE NEWARKI LEADER\nCLOW MEN\nMAKE PROTEST\nNew York Manufacturers Seek\nChanged Conditions and\nLower Wages.\nSAY BUSINESS IS HARMED\nOne of the\nOfficials\nReturn to Piece Work Is\nDemands Made\u2014Union\nPredict Fight\u2014Question May\nBe Arbitrated.\nGeneral revision of working and\nwage agreements \u201cnecessitated by\nbusiness depression and a prediction of\nlower prices\u201d is sought by the Clothing\nManufacturers\u2019 association of New\nYork in proposals adopted for presen\ntation to the Amalgamated Clothing\nWorkers\u2019 uuion. Union officials, when\napprised of the employers\u2019 demands,\nsaid it was probable counter-proposals\nwould be made and the points in dis\npute then submitted to arbitration.\nNew contracts must be drawn to en\nable the clothing Industry in New\nYork to compete with other clothing\nmarkets, the employers declared. They\nclaim the loss of business In New\nYork is more severe than In any other\nclothing center, and that wages are\nfifty per cent higher there.\nThe demands call for a return to\nthe piece-work system, the right of\nmanufacturers to establish their own\nmethods of discipline and to install\nimproved machinery to reduce labor\ncost.\nDenial that there Is a fifty per cent\nwage advance in New York over other\ncities was made by members of the\nunion, who predicted a fight against\nthe piece-work clause.\nGENERAL LABOR NEWS\nThe lack of coal is proving a men\nace to industrial Europe.\nThe state of Texas Is planning the\nbuilding of a cement plant.\nOrganized carpenters In New York\ncity are asking for a 40-hour week.\nThe Sleeping Car Conductors\u2019 union\nhas increased its membership to .more\nthat) 2,500.\nThe International Union of Marine\nEngineers now has a membership\nmore than 20.000.\nOrganized labor In Tucson, Ariz.,\nhas purchased a drug store which will\nbe operated on the co-operative plan.\nThe average wage per employee of\ntrolley workers in Philadelphia has\nbeen increased 185 per cent since 1910.\nJapanese silk manufacturers have\ndecided to reduce production until the\nend of the year owing to the break in\nprices.\nThe Switchmen\u2019s Union of North\nAmerica, from August 1, 1919, to\nAugust 1, 1920, has organized 44 new\nlocals\nA minimum wage\n65c\n60c\n60c\n70c\n30c\n$1.25\nIS\nis\nof\nY.,\nto\nAuto mechanics In Yonkers, N.\nare waging a vigorous campaign\norganize every worker in that line.\nof $17.50 weekly\nhas been obtained by a union agree\nment for women laundry workers in\nSan Francisco.\nPulp and paper making is one of\nthe important Industries of Canada,\nrepresenting a total capital Investment\nof $241,344,704.\nThe Japanese government is offer\ning financial assistance to certain In\ndustries with a view of preventing a\nserious business depression.\nCanada is to have a $5,000,000\nmatch factory which will be controlled\nby four of the biggest match manu\nfacturing firms In Great Britain.\nAn open shop policy was announced\nat Boston on the second day of the\nstrike of union taxicab drivers by\ntheir employers, following a meeting\nof the directors of the Taxi Service\ncompany, the Town Taxi company,\nCummings Bros., the Armstrong Trans\nfer company and the Fenway Garage\ncompany.\nBy a roll call vote of 1,119 to 710,\nthe International Association of Ma\nchinists In convention at Rochester,\nN. Y.. rejected a resolution offered by\nW. N. Huttie of Washington, D. C., to\nrescind three resolutions adopted fav\noring United States recognition of the\nsoviet government of Russia, opposing\nany war move by the United States\nagainst Russia and United States aid\nto Poland against Russia.\nTemporarily releasing approximate\nly 4,500 men and women workers from\nemployment, the Toledo (Ohio) plants\nof the Willys-Overland Automobile\ncompany were closed down, with the\nexception of a few departments en\ngaged In producing certain parts. In\nmaking the announcement Clarence E.\nEarl, vice president of the company,\nsaid that falling off in the demand for\nautomobiles is the cause of temporary\ncurtailment of production. Under\nnormal conditions the company em\nploys 14,000 men and women. Under\nthe changed conditions, less than 2,000\nwill be at work, it was said.\nMost of the ports of Greece have\nharbors too shallow for American\nsteamers. Moreover the Corinthian\ncanal is restricted In size.\nDuring the first six months of the\npresent year the International Mold\ners\u2019 Union of North America paid\n$163,498 to Its members In sick bene\nfits.\nGreat Britain Is making strenuous\nefforts to catch up with the United\nStates in the making of motion pic\nture films. The British Interests hope\n(eventually to make London\nthe dis\u00ad\ntributing center of the world.\nBoys\u2019 Clothes\nStyle and Good\nAppearance\nnot the principle value feature\nthese clothes, the biggest thing\nTHE WEAR.\nReal Service and Economy fadtors\nthat makes your money so well\ninvested.\n77 E. MAIN STREET\niiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiim\nBoys\u2019 Suits in Corduroy, Fancy Mixtures\nand Blue Serges\nBoys\u2019 Overcoats and Mackinaws.\nBoys\u2019 Underwear, Hosiery, Nightwear, Headwear.\nBoys\u2019 Waists and Shirts, Sweaters, Hockey Caps, Gloves\nROE EMERSON\nCOR. THIRD AND MAIN\nniiH!!!!iiii!iiiiiniiin!ii!iin!iniiiHiii!iiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiniiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii\nA Great Opportunity For\nBig Savings\nHigh Grade Tires\nON\nAND\nAutomobile Supplies\nMost every high grade accessory offered at\nDeep-Cut prices during our Great October\nSale. Ask to see our complete list of\nspecial price items.\nNEWARK AUTO SUPPLY CO\nT9T\nTRACEY BELL\nOPPOSITE POST OFFICE\nCOAL! COAL!\nOrder Your Coal From\n69 West Main Street\nAUTO PHONE 2146\niiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiniiiiim\nFRIDAY, OCTOBER 29, 1920\nn","height":"26679","width":"18609"}}
